The orthography of this MS. also bears evidence of its high antiquity‚ u being employed in it to denote the sound which is uniformly expressed in other MSS. from the ninth century to the sixteenth downward by b b⁸ ff or bh. Nor should it escape our notice, that the death of a Muredachus‚ prior of Iona, is marked by the diligent and learned Colgan undet· the year 777 †. For the letter d in Muredaehus, by the rules of Gaelic orthography‚ is qui- escent, and serves merely to lengthen out the sound, in the manner of a circumfiex accent 1 : So that actually the sound of Muredachus is much the same as that of Muirchius.
